To remove an item in an array, you can use the `splice()` method or the `filter()` method.

Using `splice()`:
```javascript
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let indexToRemove = 2;
arr.splice(indexToRemove, 1);
console.log(arr); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```
Using `filter()`:
```javascript
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let indexToRemove = 2;
arr = arr.filter((item, index) => index!== indexToRemove);
console.log(arr); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

You can also use destructuring assignment to remove an element from an array:
```javascript
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let indexToRemove = 2;
[...arr.slice(0, indexToRemove),...arr.slice(indexToRemove + 1)]
 .forEach((item) => arr.push(item));
console.log(arr); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document:

1. Create a new file called `main.tex` and start with the following code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocbibind}
\usepackage{titlesec}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{cleveref}

\title{Example Document}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Section 1}
\subsection{Subsection 1.1}
\subsubsection{Subsubsection 1.1.1}

\chapter{Chapter 2}
\section{Section 2.1}
\subsection{Subsection 2.1.1}

\section{Section 3}
\subsection{Subsection 3.1}

\end{document}
```

2. Compile the `main.tex` file using the `pdflatex` command (assuming you have a PDF viewer installed):

```shell
pdflatex main.tex
```

3. After compiling, you will see that the `main.tex` file has been converted into a PDF document with a table of contents generated automatically.

In this example, we used the `tocbibind`, `titlesec`, `hyperref`, and `cleveref` packages to achieve the automatic table of contents generation. The `tocbibind` package helps to bind the table of contents and bibliography together, `titlesec` allows for customization of section titles, `hyperref` generates hyperlinks within the document, and `cleveref` provides intelligent cross-referencing capability.

To draw a chessboard in LATEX, you can use the `tikz` package and its `chessboard` library. Here's a code snippet that creates a chessboard based on a FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) string:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}

\begin{document}

% Replace FEN_STRING with the actual FEN notation you want to use.
\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}[chessboard,font=\sffamily]
  \tikzset{board/.style={chessboard,chessboard style={#1}}}
  \path[board=black] (0,0) grid (8,8);
  \foreach \i in {0,...,7}
    \draw[very thin,black] (\i*2,0) -- (\i*2,8);
    \draw[very thin,black] (0,\i*2) -- (8,\i*2);
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this code, the `\tikzset{board/.style={chessboard,chessboard style={#1}}}%` line defines a style called `board` that sets up the chessboard pattern with the given color (in this case, black). The `\path[board=black] (0,0) grid (8,8);` line creates the grid with the chessboard pattern. Finally, the `\foreach \i in {0,...,7}%` loop adds the lines separating the squares.

To use this code with your specific FEN notation, replace `FEN_STRING` in the `\path[board=black] (0,0) grid (8,8);` line with the desired FEN string. For example, if you want to display the starting position of a chess game, use `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR` as the FEN string.

